Lagos socialite, Buhari Oloto, have been charged alongside four others before a Lagos State High Court over alleged unlawful interference with property, contrary to Section 2(1) of the Lagos State Properties Protection Law 2016. Tomori Williams, Adeyemi Adewale, Jimoh Jafar and Chief Edward Akande were listed as co-defendants in the charge marked, LD/8821C/2019 and dated 18th February, 2019, which was signed by DSP Henry Obiazi, on behalf of the Inspector General of Police. The police gave the particulars of the offence as follows: “Buhari Oloto, Tomori Williams, Adeyemi Adewale, Jimoh Jafar and Chief Edward Akande, between January and April, 2016 at Alaka area of Lagos within the jurisdiction of this honourable court, unlawfully interfered with a vast expanse of land, property of the Registered Trustees of the Estate of Late Madam Iyalode Efunroye Tinubu and prevented the trustees, their lawful representatives and genuine purchaser of the portions of the said land, from making use of the said property and thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 2(3) of the Lagos State Properties Protection Law 2016.” The land was said to be in peaceful possession of the Registered Trustees of the Estate of Late Madam Iyalode Efunroye Tinubu. The trustees have given Adamakin Investments and Works Limited the power of attorney over the land. It is the company that filed a complaint to the police on behalf of the trustees. The suspects were also charged with forcible entry and possession of land contrary to Sections 3 and 4 of the Lagos State Properties Protection Law 2016. They were accused of entering the land in a manner that is likely to cause a breach of peace. Particulars of count 3 read:  “Buhari Oloto, Tomori Williams, Adeyemi Adewale, Jimoh Jafar and Chief Edward Akande between January and April, 2016 at Alaka area of Lagos within the jurisdiction of this honourable court, in a manner likely to cause a breach of peace, without a claim of right, forcibly took and held possession of the landed property of the Registered Trustees of the Estate of Late Madam Iyalode Efunroye Tinubu, located at Alaka Area of Lagos State and thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 4(3) of the Lagos State Properties Protection Law of 2016” Hearing of the matter has been fixed for 11th June, 2019, for the police to produce the accused persons.